<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1323,839,1505]" pageId="1" pageNumber="58">Head slightly produced below; mandibles forming a prominent angle; antennae shorter than body in female, shorter than, or as long as, body in male, scape blunt apically, third segment nearly as long as fourth and fifth segments combined, apical segments angular in cross section and slightly produced ectoapically; pronotum rounded­tuberculate laterally, constricted at apex and base; scutellum triangular; elytra gradually narrowed posteriorly, rounded apically; mesosternal intercoxal process broad, emarginate; hind femora not reaching apices of elytra in female, barely, or not, attaining them in male; first metatarsal segment a little longer than following two combined, somewhat compressed laterally.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1323,839,1505]" pageId="1" pageNumber="58">
The genus 
<taxonomicName box="[440,624,1159,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Embrikstrandia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[440,624,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="58">Embrikstrandia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
closely resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[846,980,1159,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Zonopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[846,980,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="58">Zonopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs in having the first and third antennal segments unspined ectoapically, the pronotum with distinct lateral tubercles, the hind femora longer, the first metarsal segment compressed and distinctly longer than the following two segments combined, and the elytra tapering posteriorly.
</paragraph>
